<chapter xml:id="chapter-poly" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Polynomial growth</title>

<!-- TODO put note about changes to integ chapter in traditional version -->

<section xml:id="section-poly-intro">
<title>Power and polynomial functions</title>

<subsection>
<title>Definitions</title>

<p>
A polynomial is the result of performing algebra in one variable when you restrict yourself to the operations of addition, subtraction, and multiplication.
(Keep in mind that a power with a positive integer exponent just represents repeated multiplication.)
The generic form of a polynomial in the variable <m>t</m> is
<me> p(t) = a_0 + a_1 t + a_2 t^2 + a_3 t^3 + \dotsb + a_{n-1} t^{n-1} + a_n t^n </me>
where we assume <m>a_n \neq 0</m>
(since otherwise we would have omitted that term and terminated the polynomial at a lower power of <m>t</m>).
The constants <m>a_0, a_1, \dotsc, a_n</m> are called the <term>coefficients</term> of the polynomial,
and the highest exponent <m>n</m> is called the <term>degree</term>.
</p>

<p>
A polynomial that consists of just a single term,
<me> p(t) = a_n t^n </me>,
is called a <term>power function</term>.
For <m>n \ge 2</m> and even,
the graph of a power function is essentially a parabola,
while for <m>n \ge 3</m> and odd,
the graph of a power function is essentially a parabola with one arm flipped vertically.
In both cases, higher values of <m>n</m> flatten out the bottom and steepen the sides.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-poly-powers">
	<caption>Graphs of basic power functions.</caption>

	<sidebyside valign="middle" widths="54.1% 44.7%">

		<figure xml:id="figure-poly-powers-even">
			<caption>Graphs of power functions of even degree.</caption>
			<image xml:id="image-poly-even">
				<description>Graphs of power functions of even degree.</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="poly.d/even.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<figure xml:id="figure-poly-powers-odd">
			<caption>Graphs of power functions of odd degree.</caption>
			<image xml:id="image-poly-odd">
				<description>Graphs of power functions of odd degree.</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="poly.d/odd.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

	</sidebyside>

</figure>

<p>
Solving <m>p(t) = 0</m> for <m>p</m> a polynomial is of fundamental importance in algebra.
A solution to <m>p(t) = 0</m> is called a <term>root</term> of <m>p</m>,
and graphically these solutions coincide with horizontal intercepts of the polynomial's graph.
The meaning of the term <term><m>\nth</m> root</term> of a number is tied to the roots of polynomials,
as a square root <m>\sqrt{a}</m> means the (positive) root of the equation <me>t^2 - a = 0</me>,
a cube root <m>\sqrt[3]{a}</m> means the unique real root of the equation <me>t^3 - a = 0</me>,
and so on.
</p>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Polynomials of small degree</title>

<introduction><p>
	Since we often factor polynomials into factors that are polynomials of smaller degree,
	polynomials of small degree are of special interest.
</p></introduction>

<subsubsection><title>Constant polynomials</title><p>
	A polynomial of degree <m>0</m> is just a a constant function,
	and its graph is a horizontal line.
	The zero function <m>p(t) = 0</m> can be considered a polynomial,
	though, depending on the context,
	it may be appropriate to say that the zero polynomial has <em>no</em> degree to distinguish it from non-zero constant polynomials.
	However, we will just lump the zero polynomial in with the constant polynomials.
</p></subsubsection>

<subsubsection><title>Linear polynomials</title><p>
	A polynomial of degree <m>1</m>,
	<me> p(t) = a_0 + a_1 t </me>,
	is called a <term>linear polynomial</term> because its graph is a line,
	with vertical intercept <m>a_0</m> and slope <m>a_1</m>,
	as usual.
	The root of a linear polynomial is easy to determine:
	<md><mrow> a_0 + a_1 t \amp = 0 \amp \amp\implies \amp t \amp = - \frac{a_0}{a_1} </mrow></md>.
</p></subsubsection>

<subsubsection>
<title>Quadratic polynomials</title>

<p>
A polynomial of degree <m>2</m>,
<me> p(t) = a_0 + a_1 t + a_2 t^2 </me>,
is called a <term>quadratic polynomial</term>.
Its graph is always a parabola, though it may be shifted and/or reflected.
If the parabola opens upward we say that it is <term>concave up</term>,
and if it opens downward we say that it is <term>concave down</term>.
Which of these two shapes the parabola exhibits is determined by <m>a_2 \gt 0</m> or <m>a_2 \lt 0</m>,
respectively.
The <term>vertex</term> of a parabola is the point where a concave up parabola reaches its minimum height,
or where a concave down parabola reaches its maximum height.
</p>

<p>
A power function of degree <m>2</m>, <m> p(t) = a_2 t^2 </m>,
has its vertex at the origin.
For other degree-<m>2</m> polynomials,
we can determine the location of the vertex of its graph by <term>completing the square</term>.
</p>

<example>
	<title>Completing the square</title>

	<p>
	Consider polynomial <me> p(t) = 6 + 10 t - 2 t^2 </me>.
	First, we note that this parabola is concave down because of the negative coefficient on the <m>t^2</m> term.
	After factoring out that coefficient,
	we complete the square by manipulating the constant term to create a <term>perfect square</term>.
	<!-- the color command messes up the spacing in front of the plus, and \: = \medmuskip, the spacing around binary operators -->
	<md>
		<mrow> p(t) \amp = - 2 t^2 + 10 t - 6 </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = - 2 (t^2 - 5 t + 3) </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = - 2 \left( t^2 - 5 t \: {\color{red} + {\left(\frac{5}{2}\right)}^2 - {\left(\frac{5}{2}\right)}^2} + 3 \right) </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = - 2 \left[ {\left(t - \frac{5}{2}\right)}^2 - \frac{25}{4} + 3 \right] </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = - 2 \left[ {\left(t - \frac{5}{2}\right)}^2 - \frac{13}{4} \right] </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = - 2 {\left(t - \frac{5}{2}\right)}^2 + \frac{13}{2}</mrow>
	</md>
	Using our knowledge of transformations of graphs from <xref ref="section-funcs-transformations" />,
	we interpret the last formula above as a combination of transformations of the standard parabola <m>f(t) = t^2</m>,
	in the order listed:
	<ul>
		<li> horizontal shift by <m>5/2</m> to the right </li>
		<li> vertical stretch by a factor of <m>2</m> </li>
		<li> vertical reflection </li>
		<li> vertical shift by <m>13/2</m> up. </li>
	</ul>
	The two shifts put the vertex at the point <m>(5/2,13/2)</m>,
	and the vertical reflection reminds us that the parabola is concave down.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-poly-complete-the-square">
		<caption> Graph of a parabola whose shape and location were determined by completing the square. </caption>
		<image xml:id="image-poly-complete-sq" width="57%">
			<description>Graph of a parabola whose shape and location were determined by completing the square.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="poly.d/complete-sq.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<p>
By considering different shifts and vertical reflections of parabolas,
we can see that a quadratic polynomial can have no roots, one unique root, or two distinct roots.
If we write our quadratic polynomial as
<me> a t^2 + b t + c </me>,
then whether this polynomial has none, one, or two roots is determined by the <term>discriminant</term>
<me> b^2 - 4 a c </me>.
<dl>

	<li>
		<title>no roots</title>
		<p>
		when <m>b^2 - 4 a c \lt 0</m>;
		a concave up parabola with vertex above the horizontal axis or a concave down parabola with vertex below the horizontal axis
		</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>one unique root</title>
		<p>
		when <m>b^2 - 4 a c = 0</m>;
		a parabola with vertex on the horizontal axis
		</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>two distinct roots</title>
		<p>
		when <m>b^2 - 4 a c \gt 0</m>;
		a concave up parabola with vertex below the horizontal axis or a concave down parabola with vertex above the horizontal axis
		</p>
	</li>

</dl>
In any case,
there exists a formula for the roots of quadratic polynomial.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-poly-quadratic-formula">
	<title>Quadratic formula</title>
	<p>
	If the discriminant satisfies <m>b^2 - 4 a c \ge 0</m>,
	then the roots of <me> a t^2 + b t + c = 0 </me>
	are <md><mrow> t \amp = \frac{-b - \sqrt{b^2 - 4 a c}}{2 a} \amp t \amp = \frac{-b + \sqrt{b^2 - 4 a c}}{2 a} </mrow></md>,
	where these two roots are one and the same in the case that <m>b^2 - 4 a c = 0</m>.
	</p>
</identity>

</subsubsection>

<subsubsection>
<title>Cubic polynomials</title>

<p>
The graph of a cubic polynomial often follows an <q>up-down-up</q> or <q>down-up-down</q> pattern,
as in <xref ref="figure-poly-two-cubics" />.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-poly-two-cubics">
	<caption>Typical graphs of cubic functions.</caption>

	<sbsgroup>

		<sidebyside widths="63.5%"><figure xml:id="figure-poly-two-cubics-1">
			<caption>Graph of a cubic that follows an <q>up-down-up</q> pattern.</caption>
			<image xml:id="image-poly-cubic-1">
				<description>Graph of a cubic that follows an "up-down-up" pattern.</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="poly.d/cubic-1.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure></sidebyside>

		<sidebyside widths="63.5%"><figure xml:id="figure-poly-two-cubics-2">
			<caption>Graph of a cubic that follows an <q>down-up-down</q> pattern.</caption>
			<image xml:id="image-poly-cubic-2">
				<description>Graph of a cubic that follows an "down-up-down" pattern.</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="poly.d/cubic-2.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure></sidebyside>

	</sbsgroup>

</figure>

<p>
The axes have been intentionally omitted from the graphs in <xref ref="figure-poly-two-cubics" />,
so that you can imagine different vertical shifts of these graphs.
In particular, the dashed lines indicate different possible locations of the horizontal axis,
demonstrating the possibility for one, two, or three roots for a cubic polynomial.
</p>

</subsubsection>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Roots and factoring</title>

<p>
The shape of graphs and roots of higher degree polynomials is obviously more complicated.
There exist formulas for the roots of cubic and quartic (degree-<m>4</m>) polynomials similar to the <xref ref="pattern-poly-quadratic-formula" />,
but already there is (famously) no such general formula possible for quintic (degree-<m>5</m>) polynomials.
However, we can say something about the <em>number</em> of roots of a polynomial.
</p>

<theorem xml:id="theorem-poly-fundamental">
	<title>Fundamental Theorem of Algebra</title>
	<p> A polynomial of degree <m>n</m> can have no more than <m>n</m> roots. </p>
</theorem>

<p> The reason for this is that solving for roots and factoring are equivalent tasks. </p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-poly-factor-root">
	<title>Root implies linear factor</title>
	<p>
	If <m>p(t)</m> is a polynomial of degree <m>n</m>,
	then <m>t = a</m> is a root of <m>p(t) = 0</m> if and only if there exists a polynomial <m>q(t)</m> of degree <m>n - 1</m> so that
	<me> p(t) = (t - a) q(t) </me>.
	</p>
</identity>

<p>
<xref ref="pattern-poly-factor-root" /> is the reason the <xref ref="theorem-poly-fundamental" text="title" /> is true:
if every root means we can factor out a linear factor,
then <m>n</m> roots means <m>n</m> linear factors,
at which point we will have reached the degree of the polynomial and can factor no further.
</p>

<example>
	<title>Factoring out a root</title>

	<p>
	Clearly <m>t = -1</m> is a root of <m>p(t) = t^4 - 1</m>.
	This means that we can factor
	<me> \bbrac{t - (-1)} = (t + 1) </me>
	out of <m>p</m>.
	</p>

	<tabular halign="center">
		<row>
			<cell />
			<cell bottom="minor"><m>\color{red} t^3</m></cell>
			<cell bottom="minor"><m>\color{blue} -</m></cell>
			<cell bottom="minor"><m>\color{blue} t^2</m></cell>
			<cell bottom="minor"><m>\color{green} +</m></cell>
			<cell bottom="minor"><m>\color{green} t</m></cell>
			<cell bottom="minor"><m>\color{purple} -</m></cell>
			<cell bottom="minor"><m>\color{purple} 1</m></cell>
			<cell bottom="minor" />
			<cell bottom="minor" />
		</row>
		<row>
			<cell right="minor"><m>t + 1</m></cell>
			<cell><m>t^4</m></cell>
			<cell><m>+</m></cell>
			<cell><m>0 t^3</m></cell>
			<cell><m>+</m></cell>
			<cell><m>0 t^2</m></cell>
			<cell><m>+</m></cell>
			<cell><m>0 t</m></cell>
			<cell><m>-</m></cell>
			<cell><m>1</m></cell>
		</row>
		<row>
			<cell><m>-</m></cell>
			<cell bottom="minor"><m>\color{red} t^4</m></cell>
			<cell bottom="minor"><m>\color{red} +</m></cell>
			<cell bottom="minor"><m>\color{red} t^3</m></cell>
			<cell />
			<cell><m>\downarrow</m></cell>
			<cell />
			<cell><m>\downarrow</m></cell>
			<cell />
			<cell><m>\downarrow</m></cell>
		</row>
		<row>
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell><m>- t^3</m></cell>
			<cell><m>+</m></cell>
			<cell><m>0 t^2</m></cell>
		</row>
		<row>
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell><m>-</m></cell>
			<cell bottom="minor"><m>\color{blue} - t^3</m></cell>
			<cell bottom="minor"><m>\color{blue} -</m></cell>
			<cell bottom="minor"><m>\color{blue} t^2</m></cell>
		</row>
		<row>
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell><m>t^2</m></cell>
			<cell><m>+</m></cell>
			<cell><m>0 t</m></cell>
		</row>
		<row>
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell><m>-</m></cell>
			<cell bottom="minor"><m>\color{green} t^2</m></cell>
			<cell bottom="minor"><m>\color{green} +</m></cell>
			<cell bottom="minor"><m>\color{green} t</m></cell>
		</row>
		<row>
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell><m>- t</m></cell>
			<cell><m>-</m></cell>
			<cell><m>1</m></cell>
		</row>
		<row>
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell bottom="minor"><m>\color{purple} - t</m></cell>
			<cell bottom="minor"><m>\color{purple} -</m></cell>
			<cell bottom="minor"><m>\color{purple} 1</m></cell>
		</row>
		<row>
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell />
			<cell><m>0</m></cell>
		</row>
	</tabular>

	<p>
	The remainder of <m>0</m> tells us that <m>t + 1</m> does indeed divide evenly into <m>t^4 - 1</m>,
	and the quotient result at the top says
	<me> t^4 - 1 = (t + 1) (t^3 - t^2 + t - 1) </me>.
	</p>

</example>

<fact>
	<title>Factorization of polynomials</title>
	<p>
	Every polynomial can be factored into a product of
	<ul>
		<li>
			a constant,
			by factoring out the <q>leading</q> coefficient <m>a_n</m>
		</li>
		<li>
			some number of linear factors <m>(t - r)</m>,
			where each such <m>r</m> is a root of the polynomial
		</li>
		<li>
			some number of <term>irreducible</term> quadratic factors <m>(t^2 + b t + c)</m>,
			where <m>b^2 - 4 c \lt 0 </m>, so that the quadratic has no roots and cannot be factored further.
		</li>
	</ul>
	</p>
</fact>

</subsection>

</section>


<section xml:id="section-poly-constant-var">
<title>Constant rate of variation</title>

<p>
The simplest type of polynomial is a constant function,
which can be considered a degree-0 polynomial.
We have already seen in <xref ref="pattern-vars-constant-rate" /> that a constant rate of variation always corresponds to a linear quantity function.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-poly-constant-accel">
	<title>Constant acceleration</title>

	<p>
	Variation in the velocity of an objection in motion is called <term>acceleration</term>.
	A small object dropped over the surface of an airless planet will experience constant acceleration toward the planet's surface.
	We usually denote this constant acceleration as <m>g</m>,
	since its cause is gravity.
	If we measure velocity in metres per second,
	then variation of velocity measures how many metres per second change we have per second,
	so that <m>g</m> is measured in metres per second per second
	(or <q>metres per second-squared</q>).
	</p>

	<p>
	If the object is dropped with initial velocity
	<quantity>
		<mag>0</mag>
		<unit base="metre" />
		<per  base="second" />
	</quantity>,
	then we can use either <xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-integ-to-quantity-function" />
	(just as in <xref ref="example-integ-constant-rate-to-linear" />)
	or <xref ref="pattern-vars-constant-rate" />
	to compute its velocity at any point in time after that,
	up until the time that the object hits the surface of the planet:
	<me> v(t) = 0 + \ccmint{0}{t}{g}{u} = g t </me>.
	</p>

</example>

<identity xml:id="pattern-poly-constant-rate">
	<title>Constant rate of variation</title>
	<p>
	If a quantity experiences a constant rate of variation <m>r(t) = c</m>
	then the quantity itself can be modelled by a linear function
	<me> q(t) = c t + q_0 </me>
	where <m>q_0 = q(0)</m> is the initial amount.
	</p>
</identity>

<p> <xref ref="pattern-poly-constant-rate" /> can be interpreted in reverse as well. </p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-poly-linear-quantity">
	<title>Linear quantity model</title>
	<p>
	If a quantity is modelled by a linear function
	<me> q(t) = m t + b </me>,
	then the rate of variation is constant,
	equal to the slope of the linear function's graph:
	<me> r(t) = m </me>.
	</p>
</identity>

<p>
While <xref ref="pattern-poly-constant-rate" /> is just a restatement of
<xref ref="pattern-vars-constant-rate" />,
<xref ref="pattern-poly-linear-quantity" /> is new,
though it should have been expected.
We will verify this new statement mathematically
in <xref ref="chapter-deriv" />.
<!-- in a later chapter. -->
</p>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-poly-linear-var">
<title>Linear rate of variation</title>

<p> Next we consider a linear rate of variation. </p>

<example xml:id="example-poly-linear-velo">
	<title>Linear velocity</title>

	<p>
	In <xref ref="example-poly-constant-accel" />,
	we saw that a constant acceleration model led to a linear velocity model.
	But velocity itself is the rate of variation of position.
	So we can integrate velocity to obtain a model of the accumulation of distance from the starting position,
	otherwise known as <term>displacement</term>.
	</p>

	<p>
	To simplify things, let us label the starting position as <q>position 0</q> so that displacement is the same as position.
	Our rate function is <m>v(t) = g t</m> over a time domain beginning at <m>t = 0</m> and ending at the variable time <m>t = z</m>.
	Since our graph is linear,
	we can easily compute the accumulation for this rate function as an area under the graph,
	similarly to <xref ref="example-integ-accumulation-from-area" />.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-poly-linear-accumulation-from-area">
		<caption> Accumulation of displacement as net oriented area under a velocity graph. </caption>
		<image xml:id="image-poly-linear-accumulation-from-graph" width="46.7%">
			<description>Graph of a velocity function with bounded oriented area as accumulation of displacement.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="poly.d/linear-accumulation-from-graph.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>
	The triangle in <xref ref="figure-poly-linear-accumulation-from-area" /> has height <m>v(t)</m> and base length <m>t</m>.
	So, using the formula for area of a triangle,
	we obtain
	<me> \ccmint{0}{t}{v(u)}{u} = \frac{v(t) \cdot t}{2} = \frac{g t^2}{2} </me>.
	</p>

	<p> Let's ask Sage to confirm this for us. </p>

	<sage>
		<input>
			var('g,t,u')
			v(u) = g * u
			v.integrate(u, 0, t)
		</input>
		<output> 1/2*g*t^2 </output>
	</sage>

	<p> So it seems that a linear rate function leads to parabolic growth/decay. </p>

</example>

<p>
We can combine the pattern of the result of <xref ref="example-poly-linear-velo" />
with <xref ref="pattern-poly-constant-rate" /> to deal with all linear rate functions,
since <xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props-additive" text="type-local">Property</xref>
of <xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props" /> says that
<me> \ccmint{0}{t}{ m u + b }{u} = \ccmint{0}{t}{ m u }{u} + \ccmint{0}{t}{ b }{u} </me>.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-poly-linear-rate">
	<title>Linear rate of variation</title>
	<p>
	If a quantity experiences a linear rate of variation in the form <m>r(t) = m t + b</m>
	then the quantity itself can be modelled by the quadratic function
	<me> q(t) = \frac{m}{2} t^2 + b t + q_0 </me>
	where <m>q_0 = q(0)</m> is the initial amount.
	</p>
</identity>

<example xml:id="example-poly-parabolic-motion">
	<title>Parabolic motion</title>

	<p>
	An object is thrown upwards from the surface of an airless planet with an initial velocity of <m>v_0</m> metres per second.
	We would like to model the height of the object above the planet's surface as a function in time.
	We start as before with the acceleration function <m>a(t)</m>.
	As the object is initially moving <em>upwards</em> and the gravity of the planet pulls the object <em>downwards</em>,
	this time we will take the constant acceleration to be a negative function:
	<me> a(t) = - g </me>, where <m>g</m> represents the acceleration due to gravity in metres per second per second.
	Since acceleration is the rate of variation of velocity,
	<xref ref="pattern-poly-constant-rate" />
	tells us that the velocity of the object can be modelled as
	<me> v(t) = -g t + v_0 </me>.
	And velocity is the rate of variation of position,
	so from <xref ref="pattern-poly-constant-rate" />,
	the position of the object (as a height above the surface) can be modelled as
	<me> s(t) = -\frac{g}{2} t^2 + v_0 t </me>
	if we take the initial position to be <m>s(0) = 0</m> at the surface of the planet.
	</p>

	<p>
	There are some natural questions about the object's motion that arise.
	<ul>

		<li>
			<title>When does the object return to the surface?</title>
			<p>
			To answer this,
			we want to solve for <m>t</m> in the instances where <m>s(t) = 0</m>.
			We can do this by factoring;
			for convenience we will also factor out the fraction.
			<me> s(t) = -\frac{g}{2} t^2 + v_0 t = \frac{t}{2} ( - g t + 2 v_0 ) </me>
			From the factored form,
			we can see that the object will be at the position of the surface when <m>t = 0</m>
			(as we assumed)
			and when
			<md>
				<mrow> - g t + 2 v_0 = 0 </mrow>
				<mrow> \implies \quad t = \frac{2 v_0}{g} </mrow>
			</md>.
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<title>With what velocity does it strike the surface?</title>
			<p>
			We just need to substitute the time of return into the velocity model:
			<me> v(2 v_0 / g) = - g (2 v_0 / g) + v_0 = - v_0 </me>.
			Considering the symmetry of the parabolic position function (see <xref ref="figure-poly-parabolic-motion" />)
			it makes sense that the object returns to the surface at the same speed that it left the surface,
			but oppositely directed.
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<title> When does the object reach its maximum height? </title>
			<p>
			From the symmetry of the parabolic position function (again see <xref ref="figure-poly-parabolic-motion" />),
			we expect that the object will reach its maximum height halfway between its departure from and return to the surface,
			at <me> t = \frac{v_0}{g} </me>.
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<title>
				What is the maximum height achieved?
				What is the velocity at the instant the maximum height is reached?
			</title>
			<p>
			Substituting the <q>halfway</q> time into the position and velocity functions,
			we have
			<md>
				<mrow> \text{max height} = s(v_0 / g) = \frac{v_0^2}{2 g} </mrow>
				<mrow> v(v_0 / g) = 0 </mrow>
			</md>.
			The fact that the velocity is <m>0</m> at the maximum height should not be a surprise <mdash />
			when the object is thrown upwards,
			it immediately begins to slow down because of gravity pulling back down,
			until it momentarily stops at its maximum height before beginning to descend.
			</p>
		</li>

	</ul>
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-poly-parabolic-motion">
		<caption> A position and velocity graph for parabolic motion due to gravity. </caption>
		<image xml:id="image-poly-parabolic-motion" width="61.1%">
			<description>A position and velocity graph for parabolic motion due to gravity.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="poly.d/parabolic-motion.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-poly-higher-degree-var">
<title>Polynomial rate of variation</title>

<p>
A pattern is beginning to emerge:
<ul>
	<li> a constant rate model leads to a linear quantity model </li>
	<li> a linear rate model leads to a quadratic quantity model. </li>
</ul>
We might guess that a quadratic rate model should lead to a cubic quantity model.
Let's ask Sage.
</p>

<sage>
	<input>
		var('t')
		r(x) = x^2
		r.integrate(x, 0, t)
	</input>
	<output> 1/3*t^3 </output>
</sage>

<p>
It's true!
(With some work, this could be verified using lower and upper Riemann sums.)
Because of <xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props-homogeneity" text="type-local">Property</xref>
and <xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props-additive" text="type-local">Property</xref>
of <xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props" />,
we only need a pattern for rate functions that are a power of <m>t</m> in order to be able to handle any polynomial rate function,
and that pattern appears to be
<md><mrow xml:id="equation-poly-int-pattern" tag="star"> \ccmint{0}{t}{u^m}{u} = \frac{t^{m + 1}}{m + 1} </mrow></md>.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-poly-quantity-from-rate">
	<title>Obtaining a quantity model from a polynomial rate function</title>
	<p>
	For rate function <me> r(t) = 3 t^5 - 37 t^4 + 22 t^3 + 7 t^2 - t + 56 </me>,
	the associated quantity model is <me> q(t) = 3 \cdot \frac{t^6}{6} - 37 \cdot \frac{t^5}{5} + 22 \cdot \frac{t^4}{4} + 7 \cdot \frac{t^3}{3} - \frac{t^2}{2} + 56 t + q_0 </me>,
	where <m>q_0 = q(0)</m> is the initial quantity.
	</p>
</example>

<p>
In fact,
the pattern of <xref ref="equation-poly-int-pattern" /> is valid for <em>all</em> constant exponents <m>m</m>,
with one important exception that we state below.
But because negative powers of <m>t</m> exhibit singular behaviour at <m>t = 0</m>,
we'll have to choose another time to act as the <q>initial</q> time.
The next logical choice for a <q>standard</q> initial time is <m>t = 1</m> for domains of positive time.
Let's ask Sage about accumulation for rate function <m>r(t) = t^{-2}</m> on a domain starting at <m>t = 1</m> and ending at a variable time.
Note the extra <c>assume</c> command in this code block,
where we tell Sage a little extra information about our variable domain end time so that Sage knows we are avoiding the singularity at <m>t = 0</m>
</p>

<sage>
	<input>
		var('t')
		assume(t &gt; 1)
		r(x) = x^(-2)
		r.integrate(x, 1, t)
	</input>
	<output> -1/t + 1 </output>
</sage>

<p>
If we rewrite the Sage result as <me> \frac{t^{-1}}{-1} + 1 </me>,
then it essentially fits the pattern of <xref ref="equation-poly-int-pattern" /> for <m>m = -2</m>,
and we can think of the extra <em>plus-<m>1</m></em> as an <q>initial value correction term</q>
from the fact that we have shifted our <q>initial</q> time.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-poly-int-power">
	<title>Integral of a power of <m>t</m></title>

	<ol>
		<li xml:id="pattern-poly-int-power-positive-exp">
			<title>Positive exponents</title>
			<p>
			For every positive, real value of exponent <m>m</m>,
			<me> \ccmint{0}{t}{u^m}{u} = \frac{t^{m + 1}}{m + 1} </me>
			for <m>t \ge 0 </m>.
			</p>
		</li>
		<li xml:id="pattern-poly-int-power-negative-exp">
			<title>Negative exponents</title>
			<p>
			For every negative, real value of exponent <m>m</m> <em>except</em> <m>m = -1</m>,
			<me> \ccmint{1}{t}{u^m}{u} = \frac{t^{m + 1} - 1}{m + 1} </me>
			for <m>t \gt 0 </m>.
			</p>
		</li>
	</ol>

</identity>

<p> The case of <me> \ccmint{1}{t}{\frac{1}{u}}{u} </me> is a special one that we will explore in the next chapter. </p>

<remark>
	<title>Negative domains</title>

	<p>
	The results of <xref ref="pattern-poly-int-power" /> hold over negative domains as well.
	The formula for positive exponents is valid as-is for <m>t \lt 0</m>,
	as long as the rate function <m>r(t) = t^m</m> is defined there.
	(For example, the formula would <em>not</em> be valid for <me> r(t) = t^{1/2} = \sqrt{t} </me>,
	since that rate function is only defined for <m>t \ge 0</m>.)
	For negative exponents,
	a very similar formula can be obtained for <m>t \lt 0</m> using a lower bound of <m>t = -1</m>,
	again for those exponents where a negative domain makes sense for the rate function.
	</p>

	<p>
	Also note that for a power of <m>t</m> whose domain extends into the negatives,
	its graph will always exhibit either even or odd symmetry,
	so accumulation over a negative domain can always be determined from the accumulation over the <q>mirror image</q> positive domain,
	and then taking into account the symmetry of those two accumulation areas under the rate graph.
	</p>

</remark>

<p> Finally, let's record the pattern for polynomials that we used in <xref ref="example-poly-quantity-from-rate" />. </p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-poly-quantity-from-rate">
	<title>Integral of a polynomial</title>
	<p>
	For rate function <me> r(t) = r_0 + r_1 t + r_2 t^2 + \dotsb + r_m t^m </me>,
	we have
	<me> \ccmint{0}{t}{r(u)}{u} = r_0 t + \frac{r_1}{2} t^2 + \frac{r_2}{3} t^3 + \dotsb + \frac{r_{m - 1}}{m} t^m + \frac{r_m}{m + 1} t^{m + 1} </me>.
	</p>
</identity>

<example xml:id="example-poly-definite-integral">
	<title>Using <xref ref="pattern-poly-int-power" /> and <xref ref="pattern-poly-quantity-from-rate" /></title>
	<p>
	Suppose we want to compute <me> \ccmint{2}{5}{ 4 - 5 t^2 + 9 t^{13} + \frac{11}{t^4} }{t} </me>.
	The formulas
	in <xref ref="pattern-poly-int-power" />
	and <xref ref="pattern-poly-quantity-from-rate" />
	involve a lower bound of <m>0</m> or <m>1</m>.
	We can use the properties in <xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props" /> to change the bounds of integration to match.
	<md>

		<mrow> \amp \ccmint{2}{5}{ 4 - 5 t^2 + 9 t^3 + \frac{11}{t^4} }{t} </mrow>

		<mrow>
			\amp
			= \ccmint{2}{5}{ 4 - 5 t^2 + 9 t^3 }{t}
			+ 11 \ccmint{2}{5}{ t^{-4} }{t} \amp \amp\text{(i)}
		</mrow>

		<mrow>
			\amp =
			\left(
				\ccmint{0}{5}{ 4 - 5 t^2 + 9 t^3 }{t}
				- \ccmint{0}{2}{ 4 - 5 t^2 + 9 t^3 }{t}
			\right)
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp \qquad {} +
			11 \left(
				\ccmint{1}{5}{ t^{-4} }{t}
				- \ccmint{1}{2}{ t^{-4} }{t}
			\right)
			\amp \amp\text{(ii)}
		</mrow>

		<mrow>
			\amp =
			\bbrac{
				(4 \cdot 5 - \frac{5}{3} \cdot 5^3 + \frac{9}{4} 5^4)
				- (4 \cdot 2 - \frac{5}{3} \cdot 2^3 + \frac{9}{4} 2^4)
			}
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp \qquad {} +
			11 \left(
				\frac{5^{-3} - 1}{-3}
				- \frac{2^{-3} - 1}{-3}
			\right)
			\amp \amp\text{(iii)}
		</mrow>

		<mrow> \amp = \frac{1187679}{1000} </mrow>

	</md>
	The steps above are justified as follows.
	<ol marker="(i)">

		<li>
			<xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props-homogeneity" text="type-local">Property</xref>
			and <xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props-additive" text="type-local">Property</xref>
			of <xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props" />.
		</li>

		<li>
			<xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props-split" text="type-local">Property</xref>
			of <xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props" />,
			where we use
			<md alignment="gather">
				<mrow>
					\ccmint{0}{5}{ 4 - 5 t^2 + 9 t^3 }{t}
					= \ccmint{0}{2}{ 4 - 5 t^2 + 9 t^3 }{t} + \ccmint{2}{5}{ 4 - 5 t^2 + 9 t^3 }{t}
				</mrow>
				<mrow>
					\ccmint{1}{5}{ t^{-4} }{t}
					= \ccmint{1}{2}{ t^{-4} }{t} + \ccmint{2}{5}{ t^{-4} }{t}
				</mrow>
			</md>.
			Note that we have used a lower bound of <m>0</m> for the first integral and a lower bound of <m>1</m> for the second to match the different cases of
			<xref ref="pattern-poly-int-power" />.
		</li>

		<li>
			Applying <xref ref="pattern-poly-quantity-from-rate" /> to the first pair of integrals
			and <xref ref="pattern-poly-int-power-negative-exp" text="type-local">Formula</xref>
			from <xref ref="pattern-poly-int-power" /> to the second pair.
		</li>

	</ol>
	</p>
</example>

</section>

